{"amendments":[{"body":"Restore snapshot-based `plan_hash` backfill when creating a new running row. In `src/adapters/fs.rs:3034-3047`, `record_task_run_start` now writes `plan_hash: None` whenever the caller omits `plan_hash`, even though the milestone snapshot already contains the canonical hash from `persist_plan()`. That regresses the accepted lineage contract: fresh start rows, `BeadStarted` journal details, and in-flight lineage reads now lose the plan version immediately, and if the snapshot advances before completion the row can stay unattributed forever. The updated expectations at `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:4764-4791`, `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:4917-4941`, and `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:5106-5162` lock in the wrong behavior instead of catching it.","rationale":"`record_bead_start` already serializes with `persist_plan()` under `with_milestone_write_lock`, so the new race-based rationale does not justify dropping the backfill on the production path."},{"body":"Reinstate open-row `plan_hash` backfill for existing running attempts whose row still has `plan_hash: None`. The new `None => false` branch in `src/adapters/fs.rs:2596-2616` means a pre-plan or legacy running entry can no longer be repaired after a plan exists, even when replaying the same open start. That contradicts the accepted open-entry backfill requirement and leaves those attempts permanently unattributed. The regression is now asserted by `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:5166-5273`.","rationale":"This breaks the supported recovery path where a start was recorded before `persist_plan()` and later revisited; subsequent completion and lineage queries will never recover the canonical plan hash."}],"summary":"Reviewed `HEAD^..HEAD` in `src/adapters/fs.rs`, `src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs`, and `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs`. I found 2 correctness regressions, both in the new `plan_hash` behavior: new start rows no longer capture the snapshot hash, and existing open rows with `plan_hash: None` are no longer repairable. I did not find a new issue in the shared journal-detail structs or the runless-to-named completion matching path."}